$ Windows Settings: System -> Multitasking

The → Windows/settings tab *System -> Multitasking* can be opened from the command line like so:
code {
start ms-settings:multitasking
code }

{ Snap Windows

  Automatically resize and arrange windows on screens.

}
{ Desktops

  Taskbar and Alt+Tab

}
{ Timeline

  Removed in Windows 11

}
{ Alt+Tab #win-settings-multitasking-alt-tab

  Define what *Alt+Tab* shows.

  options are:
    • Open windows and all tabs in Microsoft Edge
    • Open windows and five most recent tabs in Edge
    • Open windows and three most recent tabs in Edge
    • Open Windows only

  This behavior can be configured in the → Windows/registry with the value → Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_CURRENT_USER/Software/Microsoft/Windows/CurrentVersion/Explorer/Advanced#reg-no-edge-tabs[`MultiTaskingAltTabFilter`] under th
  registry key `→ Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_CURRENT_USER/Software/Microsoft/Windows/CurrentVersion/Explorer/Advanced`.

}
{ Title bar window shake

  If grabbing and shaking a window's title bar minimizes all other windows.

}
{ Virtual Desktops

  Removed in Windows 11?

}
